# React Best Practices

## Component Structure
1. Use functional components with hooks
2. Keep components small and focused (single responsibility)
3. Use TypeScript for type safety
4. Implement proper error boundaries

## State Management
1. Use useState for local state
2. Use useReducer for complex state logic
3. Use Context for global state (auth, theme)
4. Consider Zustand or Redux for large apps

## Performance
1. Use React.memo for expensive components
2. Use useMemo for expensive calculations
3. Use useCallback for function props
4. Implement lazy loading with React.lazy
5. Use virtualization for large lists (react-window)

## Code Example:
```tsx
// Good: Memoized component with proper types
interface ItemProps {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  onClick: (id: string) => void;
}

const Item = React.memo<ItemProps>(({ id, name, onClick }) => {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => onClick(id), [id, onClick]);
  return <div onClick={handleClick}>{name}</div>;
});
```

# TypeScript Best Practices

## Type Definitions
1. Always define explicit types
2. Use interfaces for objects
3. Use type for unions/intersections
4. Avoid 'any' - use 'unknown' if needed

## Code Examples:
```typescript
// Good: Explicit types
interface User {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  role: 'admin' | 'user';
}

// Good: Generic function
function getFirst<T>(arr: T[]): T | undefined {
  return arr[0];
}

// Good: Type guard
function isUser(obj: unknown): obj is User {
  return (
    typeof obj === 'object' &&
    obj !== null &&
    'id' in obj &&
    'email' in obj
  );
}

// Good: Async function with proper types
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User | null> {
  try {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
    if (!res.ok) return null;
    return res.json();
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
}
```
